SIMPLE: excursion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Excursion
<hw>Ex*cur"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>excursio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>excursion</ets>. See <er>Excurrent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
running or going out or forth; an expedition; a sally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Far on <qex>excursion</qex> toward the gates of hell.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They would make <qex>excursions</qex> and waste the country.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A journey chiefly for recreation; a pleasure trip; a
brief tour; <as>as, an <ex>excursion</ex> into the
country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A wandering from a subject; digression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am not in a scribbling mood, and shall therefore make no
<qex>excursions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>Length of stroke, as of a piston;
stroke. [An awkward use of the word.]</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Journey; tour; ramble; jaunt. See
<er>Journey</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Excursionist</ent>⟦br⟧
